This document describes the principles underlying the AI implementation for DD Poker 2.
\par 
\par }{\b\f37\insrsid14556939 Introduction}{\f4\insrsid14556939 
\par 
\par When someone
 buys a simulation product for poker, is their goal to play better poker against computer opponents?  Probably not.  They're probably looking to improve their game against real people.  If so, then it's important that they practice against players who pla
y realistically.  Sound poker strategy is an important part of any worthy computer opponent, but the players in a typical game rarely play that way.
\par 
\par To improve their chances in a real tournament, a player doesn't need an opponent that can beat them as much as they need an opponent that can }{\i\f38\insrsid14556939 teach}{\f4\insrsid14556939 
 them.  Rather than opponents who never go on tilt, who never throw their chips around recklessly, and never grow tired or bored of the game, they need opponents who do all of those things, because that's exactly wha
t real people do.  Rather than advice on how to play a hand that's based on extensive and complex computations that the player can neither fully understand nor perform in their head, a player needs advice explained in terms of simple concepts that they ca
n apply at the table.
\par 
\par This document seeks to explain some of the concepts behind our efforts to make DD Poker 2 a world class teaching tool for tournament Texas Hold'em.
\par 
\par }{\b\f37\insrsid14556939 Comparison to Other Products}{\f4\insrsid14556939 
\par 
\par The AI in DD Poker 1 was built on a decision tree.  
\par 
\par Decision trees are weak for a few reasons.
\par 
\par 1. Good poker thinking doesn't map well to a tree.
\par 2. They are predictable, and inevitably have exploitable blind spots.
\par 3. Varying styles of play aren't easily represented.
\par 
\par The AI in Poker Academy (our most credible AI competitor) is built on modeling and simulation.
\par 
\par This approach can produce strong play, but has other weaknesses.
\par 
\par 1. It's difficult to learn from because it can't explain its decisions.
\par 2. Irrational behaviors of real human players can't be easily incorporated.
\par 
\par The AI in DD Poker 2 is designed the following priorities:
\par 
\par 1. Realism, to better prepare one for games with human players.
\par 2. Strength, to keep good players challenged, and encourage better play.
\par 3. Transparency, to explain decision-making in detail, for teaching purposes.
\par 4. Flexibility, to create configurations that represent different styles of play.
\par 
\par }{\b\f37\insrsid14556939 Poker Engine Structure
\par }{\f4\insrsid14556939 
\par The AI in DD Poker 2 is basically a rule engine that considers many sem
i-independent influencers.  The result is a very flexible algorithm without structural blind spots, which can be enhanced and adjusted intuitively, can simulate irrational behaviors, and can support its decision-making with detailed explanations.
\par 
\par The proc
ess of making a decision is always basically the same; each valid outcome is assigned a score representing the accumulated weights of every rule, and the outcome with the highest score is recommended.  By presenting the individual contributions of each ru
l
e, a good basic explanation of the decision is possible.  This transparency is enhanced by the fact that the outcomes considered are tactical options, rather than poker actions with no associated intent.  Instead of considering simply whether to bet after
 the flop, the DD Poker 2 performs a separate evaluation for each of several basic motivations for betting; a bet for value, a continuation bet, a stone cold bluff, etc.
\par 
\par Where a bet amount is required, the winning outcome dictates a bet range, relative to 
a value that depends on the situation; the size of the big blind, the size of the pot, the size of the player's stack, etc.  From this range, a value is selected randomly, to avoid telltale betting patterns.
\par 
\par }{\i\f38\insrsid14556939 Basic Decision Factors
\par }{\f4\insrsid14556939 
\par Influences on the decision-making process fall into several broad categories.  The influence of each factor is determined by mathematical computations of varying complexity, many of which can be adjusted to represent different styles of play.
\par 
\par 1. Hand Strength
\par 
\par These factors range from simple pre-selected categorization of starting hands to computation-intensive analysis of the chance of drawing the best hand with cards to come, weighted with respect to hands likely to be held by remaining opponents.
\par 
\par 2. Current Situation
\par 
\par These factors include actions by each player so far in the hand, table position, pot odds, stack size, tournament strategy, and so on.
\par 
\par 3. Player Profiling
\par 
\par These factors account for patterns that have been recognized in the play of opponents still in the hand, and the table image that is likely to result from opponents performing similar analysis.
\par 
\par 4. Proclivity
\par 
\par These factors simulate tendencies that are common in human players, such as tendency to favor weak ace-blank hands, chase straights or flushes, get tired of folding and play weak hands, or go on tilt after catching a bad beat.
\par 
\par Each decision has a default outcome, which is assigned a benchmark score a
gainst which other outcomes are compared.  For example, in most pre-flop situations, the default outcome is to fold.  Without good reason to do otherwise, the AI will throw its cards away (except when unraised in the big blind of course, where the default
 is to check).  The engine computes a score for each possible alternative to the default outcome, such that a direct comparison can determine the recommended action. 
\par 
\par }{\i\f38\insrsid14556939 High-Level Situations
\par }{\f4\insrsid14556939 
\par While the basic structure of decision-making is the same in most situations, certain high-level factors have such a profound effect that different rules may be appropriate.  In pre-flop play, the following high-level scenarios are treated differently:

\par 
\par 1. Button Small Big (BSB).  Player is the button with only the blinds left in the hand.*
\par 
\par 2. No pot action; player is under the gun, or all players to the right have folded.  Single limper ignored.
\par 
\par 3. Multiple limpers.  Two or more players to the right have limped in, calling the big blind.
\par 
\par 4. Raised pot.  One raise has been put in.
\par 
\par 5. Re-raised pot.  Pot has been raised and re-raised.
\par 
\par 6. Player's stack is very short in comparison to the blinds.  Harrington calls this the Red Zone, where almost any reasonable hand will do, and the only reasonable move is to push all in.
\par 
\par In post-flop play, the only distinction with a high-level effect on the logic is whether there has been pot action yet in the current betting round.
\par 
\par }{\b\f37\insrsid14556939 Basic Quantitative Measures
\par }{\f4\insrsid14556939 
\par }{\i\f38\insrsid14556939 Position
\par }{\f4\insrsid14556939 
\par The poker literature is filled with advice on how to account for p
osition, but precise definitions of what it means to be in "early" or "late" position are rarely provided for situations other than a ten-seated table.  DD Poker 2 defines pre-flop position categories Early, Middle, Late, Small Blind, and Big Blind as fol
lows:
\par 
\par      * 10 Seats Occupied:\tab E E E M M M L L S B
\par      *  9 Seats Occupied:\tab   E E M M M L L S B
\par      *  8 Seats Occupied:\tab     E M M M L L S B
\par      *  7 Seats Occupied:\tab       M M M L L S B
\par      *  6 Seats Occupied:\tab         M M L L S B
\par      *  5 Seats Occupied:\tab           M L L S B
\par      *  4 Seats Occupied:\tab             L L S B
