\par }{\i\f38\insrsid14556939 
\par Pre-Flop Hand Strength}{\b\f37\insrsid14556939 
\par 
\par }{\f4\insrsid14556939 Due to the lack of information about other players'
 hands, hand strength before the flop is based initially on simple hand selection rules.  According to the hand selection groups in use by the player, we can assign a base score between zero and one, where hands that are not included in any group get a sc
o
re of zero, and the strongest hands get a score of one.  This is supported in the Hand Selection features of DD Poker 2 by the hand strength slider for each group, which essentially assigns a value from 1 to 10.  If these strengths are translated to score
s in a linear fashion, such that hands in groups with strengths of 1, 5, and 10 get scores of 0.1, 0.5, and 1.0 respectively.  Other adjustments for style of play and situational factors will modify this score.
\par }{\b\f37\insrsid14556939 
\par }{\i\f38\insrsid14556939 Post-Flop Hand Strength}{\b\f37\insrsid14556939 
\par }{\f4\insrsid14556939 
\par After the flop, it is possible to compute more accurate estimates of hand strength against remaining opponents, especially as their actions begin to reveal more information about their hands.  Three scores are computed for use in rule evaluation.
\par 
\par First, a Raw Hand Strength i
s calculated.  This score between 0.0 and 1.0 represents the current rank of the player's hand versus all other possible hands.  This score is of course a relatively weak representation of actual strength, since betting action before the flop can provide 
considerable information about what hands are likely to be held by remaining opponents.  For instance, an opponent who put in a large raise from early position before the flop is far more likely to be holding a high pair than two small unsuited cards.  

\par 
\par Fo
r each opponent, a table is computed that represents the best guess at the likelihood their betting behavior so far is consistent with each possible hand.**  This table is used to weight each hand in computing a Biased Hand Strength, which represents the 
current rank of the player's hand versus all }{\f4\ul\insrsid14556939 likely}{\f4\insrsid14556939  opposing hands.  
\par 
\par Last, if there are cards to come, a computation is performed to estimate the effect of the next card to be dealt, yielding a Biased Effective Hand Strength score.  Ideally this computati
on would be carried out for all remaining cards to be dealt, but this is too expensive to be practical, and has proven to have only a marginal impact on accuracy.
\par 
\par The difference between Raw Hand Strength and Biased Hand Strength can be regarded as the imp
act  on perceived hand strength of careful observation, and as such can be weighted to reflect a given player's observation skills.  The difference between Biased Hand Strength and Biased Effective Hand Strength is essentially a measure of the relative ri
sk of being outdrawn when ahead, or potential of drawing out when behind, and as such can be an important factor in betting strategy.
\par 
\par }{\i\f38\insrsid14556939 Stack Size}{\f4\insrsid14556939 
\par 
\par When a player's stack is much larger or smaller than average, certain important strategic factors kick in.  DD
 Poker 2 uses a computation similar to that described in Harrington on Hold'em as "Effective M".  This measure essentially represents how quickly the player's stack will be blinded away, by taking into account the size of the blinds and/or antes, and the 
number of players remaining at the table.  This measure is used to activate or detect both desperate and bully play.
\par 
\par }{\b\f37\insrsid14556939 Multi-Hand Statistics}{\f4\insrsid14556939 
\par 
\par A number of statistics are accumulated by the AI based on what each player could observe of hands for which they were dealt.  This information is used both to predict and interpret the actions of opponents, and to self-profile in order to take advantage o
r
 caution from shifts in table image.  As a general rule, these statistics are maintained as a weighted average of true/false conditions.  In other words, each piece of information being tracked is a simple boolean evaluation (e.g. did the player voluntari
ly put money in the pot), with the results for more recent hands being weighed more heavily.  The result is a value that both represents long-term behavior but reacts quickly to shifts in style.
\par 
\par }{\i\f38\insrsid14556939 Hands Paid}{\f4\insrsid14556939 
\par 
\par A good combined measure of looseness/aggression, this value indicates how often a player puts money in the pot voluntarily before the flop, by calling the big blind, calling a raise, or raising.  
\par 
\par }{\i\f38\insrsid14556939 Hands Limped
\par }{\f4\insrsid14556939 A good combined measure of looseness/passivity, this value indicates how often, when given the opportunity, a player calls the big bet to limp into a hand.
\par 
\par }{\i\f38\insrsid14556939 Hands Folded Unraised
\par }{\f4\insrsid14556939 A simple measure of tightness, this value indicates how often a player mucks their cards without calling an unraised big blind.
\par 
\par }{\i\f38\insrsid14556939 Hands Raised Pre-Flop
\par }{\f4\insrsid14556939 A simple measure of aggression, this value indicates how often a player raises the pot pre-flop.  
\par 
\par }{\i\f38\insrsid14556939 Post-Flop Rounds Played, Checked, Bet, and Raised
\par }{\f4\insrsid14556939 Statistics are kept on how often the player sees the flop, how often they check or fold when they do, how often they open the pot on the flop, and how often they raise.  Similar statistics are kept for the turn and the river as well.

\par 
\par }{\i\f38\insrsid14556939 Hands Over-Bet Post-flop}{\f4\insrsid14556939 
\par A simple measure of maniac or bully play, indicates how often a player puts in a bet larger than the pot , giving worse than 2 to 1 pot odds to the next player to act.
\par 
\par }{\i\f38\insrsid14556939 Hands Bet then Folded to a Raise or Re-Raise
\par }{\f4\insrsid14556939 A simple measure of how committed a player is to pots they bet into.  A high value may indicate frequent bluffing.
\par 
\par * BSB-specific strategies are not yet implemented.
\par ** Sophisticated hand probability weighting is in development.
